structure.io.pdb
Class PDBreader

java.lang.Object
  structure.io.pdb.PDBreader

public class PDBreader
extends java.lang.Object

Generic PDB reader class for reading in protein complex, protein, residue and atom information from the ATOM and HETATM entry lines in a PDB file. The only checking done concerns the allowed format and range of the numbers. Chemical validity must be checked elsewhere.

Since:
0.1
Version:
0.1
Author:
Abdullah Kahraman

createPDBreaders

public static java.util.ArrayList<PDBreader> createPDBreaders(java.lang.String infile)
                                                       throws java.io.IOException,
                                                              FileFormatException,
                                                              java.util.zip.DataFormatException
Creates list of PDBreader objects from the user given input file, where the input file can be a list of PDB files in a tar archive (.tar), compressed by GNU zip (.gz, .tar.gz, .tgz) or simply a PDB file.

Parameters:
infile - - String object holding the path to the input file.
Returns:
List of PDBreader objects each holding the content of a single PDB file.
Throws:
java.io.IOException - if input file could not be read.
FileFormatException - if ATOM or HEATM line does not conform to the PDB standards.
java.util.zip.DataFormatException - if .gz format is unknown.

getProteinComplex

public final java.util.ArrayList<PolyPeptideList> getProteinComplex(java.lang.String chainIds,
                                                                    java.lang.String alternativeLocations)
Method to read in all ATOM entries in a PDB file and convert all ATOM entries to AminoAcidType, Protein objects and return PDB file as PolyPeptideList object.

Parameters:
chainIds - - String object of all chain IDs to be used to build up the PolyPeptideList
alternativeLocations - - String object of all alternative locations to be used to build up the PolyPeptideList
Returns:
A PolyPeptideList object that consists of Protein objects, which consist themselves of AminoAcidType objects, which again consists themselves of AtomRadius objects.
